author: Babe Laufenberg
title: Laufenberg: Why Eli Manning might be losing sleep this week
text:
Babe Laufenberg, Dallas Cowboys radio color analyst and former NFL quarterback, answered your questions about the team in a chat Wednesday. Here are some highlights.
Question: What percentage of the Dallas Cowboys' playbook do you believe that Cassel has a grasp of or access to?
Babe Laufenberg: Can't say I can really put a percentage on it. The whole key is being able to react immediately to the situation. If you hesitate, even for a split second in your decision making, it is over. So his NFL experience is somewhat negated by his lack of experience in this offense. I am fond of the expression in all walks of life..."You have to know it, and know you know it." We will find out very quickly how far along he is in that process.
Question: Weeden had previously played pro baseball and things did not work out. Does being exposed to pro sports and perhaps having underachieved or not making it in baseball make him stronger going foward?
Babe Laufenberg: I hear all the time how the experience of pro baseball helps these guys when they get to the NFL. Hardens them. I wholeheartedly disagree. I will give you the example of 3 QBs the Cowboys have signed, Chad Hutchinson, Drew Henson, and now, Brandon Weeden. All were extremely high picks in baseball, failed there, then came to the NFL (Weeden after going to OSU). They went to baseball and experienced failure in their athletic careers for the first time in their lives. When I looked at Hutchinson and Henson, I saw two fragile personalities that lacked confidence. They tasted their own blood in baseball and they didn't like it. QB is all about confidence...the confidence your teammates and coaches have in you, but most importantly, the confidence you have in yourself. That confidence has been shaken. I would look long and hard before I invested in a "can't-miss-baseball prospect" who failed in baseball to be my QB.
Question: Do you feel like the Cowboys' pass rush is finally good enough with Hardy and Gregory coming back to make the difference for this team going forward?
Babe Laufenberg: Absolutely. The first half against New England was beyond impressive. Five sacks of Tom Brady? Are you kidding me? Have never seen a rush just so completely envelop Brady like that. Say what you will about Hardy, but the man was born to rush the passer. Want more good news? The last time Hardy faced the Giants, he sacked Eli Manning 3 times. As for Gregory, for a rookie to be out as long as he has, don't know quite what to expect. The NFL is a technique game, and I just wonder how good his technique can possibly be after a long layoff. Oh, wait. Rod Marinelli is coaching him...he'll be fine.
